## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | **Timeout enforcement** | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Control flow** | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Continue execution** | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |

### Why the original breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination. The `ThreadAbortException` catch and `ResetAbort` are dead code.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> for cancellation to be effective.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload — preferred in modern .NET
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// ❌ Before (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(data),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ✅ After (.NET 8) — work must accept and honor the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        foreach (var item in data)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // cooperative checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return BuildResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls for This Migration

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work ignores the token** | Cancellation is *cooperative* now. If `work` never checks `ct`, the task runs to completion regardless of the timeout. Insert `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at loop iterations and between expensive steps. |
| **Not passing token through the call chain** | If `work` calls other methods (DB queries, HTTP calls), pass `ct` to those too — most BCL I/O methods accept `CancellationToken`. |
| **Blocking I/O can't be cancelled** | Synchronous calls like `Thread.Sleep` or `socket.Receive` don't check the token. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `ct.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`, and prefer async I/O overloads. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timeout creates an internal timer. Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks — always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. Without the filter, you could swallow a caller's cancellation. |
| **Wrapping unmodifiable code** | If `work` calls a third-party library that can't accept a token, the timeout won't interrupt it. Move such work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` as a last resort. |
